<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About West Bengal</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Cultural Conscience of India</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">West Bengal is India's intellectual and artistic nerve center — a state that has given the world Rabindranath Tagore (Asia's first Nobel laureate), Satyajit Ray (one of cinema's greatest directors), Swami Vivekananda, Sri Ramakrishna, Subhas Chandra Bose, Amartya Sen and a tradition of philosophical and creative thought that has shaped modern India more profoundly than any other region. Kolkata — the City of Joy — was the capital of British India for 138 years and remains the subcontinent's most layered metropolis: a city of crumbling colonial palaces and cutting-edge theatre, of tram rides through book markets and all-night adda (intellectual conversation), of the world's finest fish preparations and the global headquarters of the sweet-making art. The state stretches with extraordinary geographic variety: from the Himalayan peaks and tea gardens of Darjeeling in the north — where the world's finest tea grows at 7,000 feet — through the industrial Gangetic plains, to the Sundarbans in the south — the world's largest mangrove forest and last home of the Bengal tiger. The Sundarbans is a UNESCO World Heritage Site of 10,000 sq km where tigers swim between islands and the tides shape daily life for fishing communities. West Bengal's Durga Puja is the world's largest art festival — 35,000 pandals across the state transform every neighbourhood into a gallery of extraordinary sculpture and lighting design, attracting UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage status in 2021. The state produced the Bengal Renaissance — a 19th-century flowering of literature, music, painting, theatre, philosophy and social reform that redefined what India could think and be. Kolkata's street food, its mishti (sweets), its Baul mystic singers, its Jatra theatre, its Pattachitra scrolls and its Kantha embroidery are each world-class traditions. West Bengal is India thinking deeply, feeling intensely, eating magnificently and celebrating without restraint.</p>
</section>

